WEBVTT

1
00:00:50.124 --> 00:00:51.458
<i>Okay, let's begin.</i>

2
00:00:57.298 --> 00:00:58.507
Who wants to start?

3
00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:00.885
Yes, Brittany, kick it off.

4
00:01:02.344 --> 00:01:04.847
I don't have a thought
on the reading,


5
00:01:04.930 --> 00:01:07.850
I just think that that word
on the board is wrong.


6
00:01:09.310 --> 00:01:11.854
Well, I think it still has
two G's in it last I checked.


7
00:01:13.022 --> 00:01:14.440
It's not funny.

8
00:01:14.523 --> 00:01:16.650
We shouldn't have to stare
at the N-word all day.


9
00:01:18.027 --> 00:01:19.028
Uh, listen,

10
00:01:20.112 --> 00:01:22.197
this is a class
on the literature


11
00:01:22.281 --> 00:01:23.574
of the American south.

12
00:01:23.657 --> 00:01:24.825
You're going to encounter

13
00:01:24.909 --> 00:01:27.578
some archaic thoughts,
coarse language,


14
00:01:27.661 --> 00:01:29.371
but we're all adults here

15
00:01:29.455 --> 00:01:31.707
and I think
we can understand it


16
00:01:31.790 --> 00:01:33.918
within the context
in which it's written.


17
00:01:34.001 --> 00:01:37.046
Well, I just find
that word really offensive.


18
00:01:37.129 --> 00:01:39.548
With all due respect, Brittany,

19
00:01:39.632 --> 00:01:42.801
I got over it,
I'm pretty sure you can too.


20
00:01:42.885 --> 00:01:43.844
Well, I don't see why.

21
00:01:48.974 --> 00:01:50.309
Right.

22
00:01:50.392 --> 00:01:52.519
Now, does anyone else have any

23
00:01:52.603 --> 00:01:53.687
thoughts
on the reading?


24
00:01:57.441 --> 00:02:00.277
Well, it made some of
your students uncomfortable.


25
00:02:00.361 --> 00:02:02.071
When did they all become
so goddamn delicate?


26
00:02:02.154 --> 00:02:03.864
This wasn't
an isolated incident.


27
00:02:03.948 --> 00:02:04.990
What?

28
00:02:05.199 --> 00:02:06.533
Last month
you asked a student


29
00:02:06.617 --> 00:02:08.535
if his family had been Nazis.

30
00:02:08.619 --> 00:02:10.120
Yeah, I did, he's German,

31
00:02:10.204 --> 00:02:11.664
we were reading
<i>The Plot Against America</i>


32
00:02:11.747 --> 00:02:14.249
and trust me, by the way
he was squirming, they were.


33
00:02:14.333 --> 00:02:15.542
Oh, my God.

34
00:02:15.626 --> 00:02:18.420
Um, Monk, you are
a very talented writer,


35
00:02:18.504 --> 00:02:20.422
we're fortunate
to have you here.


36
00:02:20.506 --> 00:02:22.967
What? He hasn't
published in years.


37
00:02:23.050 --> 00:02:24.593
I have written three novels

38
00:02:24.677 --> 00:02:26.178
since the last time
you published.


39
00:02:26.387 --> 00:02:28.055
Yeah, this is true,
and the speed
with which you write


40
00:02:28.138 --> 00:02:29.765
only proves
that good things take time.


41
00:02:29.848 --> 00:02:32.184
- Oh, go to hell, Monk.
-  Relax, Mandy.


42
00:02:32.267 --> 00:02:33.727
Yeah, relax, Mandy.

43
00:02:33.811 --> 00:02:35.521
And anyway, my new book
is with Echo


44
00:02:35.604 --> 00:02:37.690
and my agent says
they're very excited about it.


45
00:02:37.773 --> 00:02:39.525
Oh, that's great to hear.

46
00:02:39.608 --> 00:02:42.236
- What's it about?
- Can we stop stalling, Leo?


47
00:02:43.696 --> 00:02:44.863
Um...

48
00:02:44.947 --> 00:02:46.115
Listen, Monk,

49
00:02:48.367 --> 00:02:49.827
we'd like to
give you a break.


50
00:02:53.747 --> 00:02:54.790
What do you mean, break?

51
00:02:54.873 --> 00:02:56.083
Just some time off.

52
00:02:56.166 --> 00:02:57.918
Mandatory time off.

53
00:02:58.002 --> 00:03:00.587
It's just, you're already
going to Boston
for the festival, right?


54
00:03:00.671 --> 00:03:02.214
Why don't you
just stay there for--


55
00:03:02.297 --> 00:03:04.174
Because I hate Boston,
my family's there.


56
00:03:04.258 --> 00:03:05.843
Well, you need
some time to relax.


57
00:03:05.926 --> 00:03:07.386
You're on edge, man.

58
00:03:07.469 --> 00:03:08.929
You're under the impression
that time spent


59
00:03:09.013 --> 00:03:11.265
with my family
will take the edge off.


60
00:03:11.348 --> 00:03:12.933
- I'm fine.
-  You're not fine.


61
00:03:13.017 --> 00:03:14.893
I saw you crying
in your car last week.


62
00:03:14.977 --> 00:03:16.603
He punched
the steering wheel.


63
00:03:16.687 --> 00:03:17.980
Oh, wow.

64
00:03:18.063 --> 00:03:21.775
You know, if you spent
less time spying on me,


65
00:03:22.359 --> 00:03:23.318
you could

66
00:03:23.402 --> 00:03:25.404
probably write
a dozen more novels


67
00:03:25.487 --> 00:03:27.031
that people buy
at airports


68
00:03:27.114 --> 00:03:29.158
with their neck pillows
and Cheez-Its.


69
00:03:29.241 --> 00:03:31.744
Oh, here we go. Okay.
You want to go, dirty doggy?


70
00:03:31.827 --> 00:03:33.370
Okay, well, enjoy Boston.

71
00:03:33.454 --> 00:03:35.706
You can... you can get my book
at the airport.


72
00:03:35.789 --> 00:03:37.916
- Oh, and, good luck with Echo.

73
00:03:45.507 --> 00:03:47.885
<i>♪ Mm ♪</i>

74
00:03:50.262 --> 00:03:52.347
<i>♪ You turned my house ♪</i>

75
00:03:54.141 --> 00:03:55.893
<i>♪ Into a home ♪</i>

76
00:03:58.270 --> 00:04:01.732
<i>♪ You made me feel love ♪</i>

77
00:04:02.858 --> 00:04:04.359
<i>♪ I'm not alone ♪</i>

78
00:04:06.612 --> 00:04:07.821
<i>♪ And unafraid ♪</i>

79
00:04:08.655 --> 00:04:10.991
<i>♪ Yeah ♪</i>

80
00:04:11.075 --> 00:04:12.785
<i>♪ Of time to come ♪</i>

81
00:04:14.870 --> 00:04:20.793
<i>♪ Proved... ♪</i>

82
00:04:22.503 --> 00:04:27.257
<i>♪ Then you taught me how ♪</i>

83
00:04:27.341 --> 00:04:30.886
<i>♪ What it means ♪</i>

84
00:04:30.969 --> 00:04:37.059
<i>♪ Can we wake
Each and every morning
Inside a dream? ♪</i>


85
00:04:41.230 --> 00:04:42.314
Hello?

86
00:04:42.397 --> 00:04:45.901
Welcome back.
How's it feel to be home?


87
00:04:45.984 --> 00:04:47.736
<i>Great.
Already had a guy</i>


88
00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:49.988
<i>in a Bruins jersey
ask me if I think
I'm better than him.</i>


89
00:04:50.072 --> 00:04:51.907
That's good luck here.

90
00:04:51.990 --> 00:04:54.701
<i>That's Boston's version
of a ladybug landing on you.</i>


91
00:04:55.494 --> 00:04:57.496
Any news?

92
00:04:57.579 --> 00:04:59.998
Patrick at Echo is passing.
But who fucking cares?


93
00:05:00.082 --> 00:05:02.000
<i>He's an old alcoholic.</i>

94
00:05:02.084 --> 00:05:04.002
- What is that? Nine now?
-  <i>He says,</i>


95
00:05:04.086 --> 00:05:06.380
"This book is finely crafted

96
00:05:06.463 --> 00:05:09.133
with fully developed
characters and rich language,


97
00:05:09.216 --> 00:05:12.678
<i>but one is lost to understand
what this reworking of</i>


98
00:05:12.761 --> 00:05:15.430
Aeschylus' <i>The Persians</i>
has to do


99
00:05:15.514 --> 00:05:16.807
with the African-American
experience?"


100
00:05:16.890 --> 00:05:17.933
<i>There it is.</i>

101
00:05:18.016 --> 00:05:19.560
There it is.

102
00:05:19.643 --> 00:05:20.686
<i>They want
a Black book.</i>


103
00:05:20.769 --> 00:05:22.020
They have a Black book.

104
00:05:22.104 --> 00:05:24.481
I'm Black, and it's my book.

105
00:05:24.565 --> 00:05:25.899
You know what I mean.

106
00:05:25.983 --> 00:05:28.485
<i>You mean they want me
to write about</i>
a cop killing some teenager


107
00:05:28.569 --> 00:05:30.821
or a single mom in Dorchester
raising five kids.


108
00:05:30.904 --> 00:05:33.448
Dorchester is pretty white now.
But yes.


109
00:05:34.283 --> 00:05:35.409
Jesus Christ. You know,

110
00:05:35.492 --> 00:05:37.703
I don't even really believe
in race.


111
00:05:37.786 --> 00:05:40.372
<i>Yeah. The problem
is that everyone else does.</i>


112
00:05:43.375 --> 00:05:45.377
<i>Anyway, have fun
at the book festival.</i>


113
00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:49.381
<i>And just don't insult
anyone important. Please.</i>


114
00:05:53.427 --> 00:05:55.721
Writing from
a historical perspective


115
00:05:55.804 --> 00:05:57.890
doesn't mean that you can't

116
00:05:57.973 --> 00:05:59.683
make work
that doesn't resonate


117
00:05:59.766 --> 00:06:01.476
with today's audiences.

118
00:06:01.560 --> 00:06:04.980
Yeah, I think of things like
<i>Game of Thrones</i> as proof that


119
00:06:05.063 --> 00:06:08.317
nerds like us
can still find great success.


120
00:06:11.403 --> 00:06:13.363
Unfortunately, we're going
to have to end it there.


121
00:06:14.489 --> 00:06:15.574
Thank you to our authors

122
00:06:15.657 --> 00:06:17.826
and thanks to all of you
for attending.


123
00:06:19.828 --> 00:06:20.787
Um...

124
00:06:22.164 --> 00:06:24.291
Is it just me,
or was this small


125
00:06:24.374 --> 00:06:26.084
even for a book festival?

126
00:06:26.168 --> 00:06:28.545
Yeah, it's because
we're up against Sintara.


127
00:06:29.171 --> 00:06:30.339
Who?

128
00:06:30.422 --> 00:06:32.466
Sintara Golden.
You haven't read her?


129
00:06:33.926 --> 00:06:35.469
No, what's her book called?

130
00:06:37.888 --> 00:06:40.057
Raves everywhere.

131
00:06:40.140 --> 00:06:42.351
<i>The Post, Bookforum.</i>

132
00:06:42.434 --> 00:06:43.936
The <i>London Review
of Books</i> said,


133
00:06:44.019 --> 00:06:46.271
<i>"We's Lives in Da Ghetto</i>

134
00:06:46.355 --> 00:06:49.566
is a heartbreaking
and visceral debut."


135
00:06:49.650 --> 00:06:52.361
Plus a little birdie told me
that perhaps


136
00:06:52.444 --> 00:06:55.447
there's a TV adaptation
in the works?


137
00:06:55.530 --> 00:06:57.658
- No comment.

138
00:06:57.741 --> 00:06:59.868
Okay, it was worth a shot.

139
00:07:00.827 --> 00:07:02.871
Tell us, what was
your life like


140
00:07:02.955 --> 00:07:04.665
before you were an author?

141
00:07:04.748 --> 00:07:07.167
Well, I did undergrad
at Oberlin


142
00:07:07.251 --> 00:07:11.213
and moved to New York
the day after graduation


143
00:07:11.296 --> 00:07:13.048
and a couple months later,

144
00:07:13.131 --> 00:07:15.133
I was an assistant
at a publisher.


145
00:07:15.217 --> 00:07:17.761
And did
that assistant experience
shape your writing?


146
00:07:17.844 --> 00:07:21.848
Absolutely. Yeah,
I was a first reader meaning


147
00:07:21.932 --> 00:07:24.768
I would read
all the manuscripts
in the slush pile


148
00:07:24.851 --> 00:07:27.854
and send them up the ladder
if they were any good.


149
00:07:27.938 --> 00:07:30.524
Some of them were great,
most were not.


150
00:07:32.943 --> 00:07:35.779
But the feeling
I couldn't shake was that


151
00:07:35.862 --> 00:07:38.782
no matter how good
the books were,


152
00:07:38.865 --> 00:07:43.412
most every submission
was from some white dude
from New York


153
00:07:43.495 --> 00:07:44.538
going through a divorce,

154
00:07:44.621 --> 00:07:47.624
and too few of them
were about my people.


155
00:07:48.750 --> 00:07:49.751
And so I think,

156
00:07:50.585 --> 00:07:51.753
"Where are our stories?"

157
00:07:53.130 --> 00:07:55.215
You know,
"Where's our representation?"


158
00:07:55.966 --> 00:07:57.509
And it was from that lack

159
00:07:57.592 --> 00:07:59.428
that my book was born.

160
00:08:01.096 --> 00:08:03.307
Would you give us the pleasure
of reading an excerpt?


161
00:08:06.393 --> 00:08:07.394
Thank you.

162
00:08:12.816 --> 00:08:15.068
"'Yo, Cheranda,

163
00:08:15.152 --> 00:08:17.195
where you be goin'
in a hurry likes that?'


164
00:08:17.279 --> 00:08:19.990
Donna aks me when she see me
comin' out the house.


165
00:08:21.950 --> 00:08:23.493
'Ain't none ya business,

166
00:08:23.577 --> 00:08:26.747
but if'n you gots to know,
I's goin' to the pharmacy.'


167
00:08:28.123 --> 00:08:30.625
I looks back at the door
to see if Mama comin' out.


168
00:08:31.877 --> 00:08:35.255
'The pharmacy?
What for?' she aks.


169
00:08:36.423 --> 00:08:38.133
'You know', I says.

170
00:08:39.301 --> 00:08:41.011
'Nah', she say.

171
00:08:42.387 --> 00:08:45.640
'Hell, nah!
Girl, you be pregnant again?'


172
00:08:47.100 --> 00:08:48.894
'Might's be', I tells her.

173
00:08:49.853 --> 00:08:51.646
'And if I is,

174
00:08:51.730 --> 00:08:54.816
Ray-Ray's gonna be a real
father this time around.'"


175
00:08:58.153 --> 00:08:59.237
Thank you.

176
00:09:03.575 --> 00:09:04.701
Yes!

177
00:09:46.785 --> 00:09:48.078
-  Hi...
-  Hi.


178
00:09:48.161 --> 00:09:49.704
I'm here
to see Lisa Ellison.


179
00:09:49.788 --> 00:09:50.831
Uh, do you have
an appointment?


180
00:09:50.914 --> 00:09:51.957
We're about to close.

181
00:09:52.040 --> 00:09:53.583
No, I'm her brother.

182
00:09:53.667 --> 00:09:54.709
-  Oh.

183
00:09:54.793 --> 00:09:55.752
There she is.

184
00:10:00.757 --> 00:10:01.842
Hello, Monk.

185
00:10:04.761 --> 00:10:05.762
Hi, Lisa.

186
00:10:14.563 --> 00:10:17.190
Okay, you're in a boat,
the motor cuts out,


187
00:10:18.150 --> 00:10:19.860
but you're in shallow water,

188
00:10:19.943 --> 00:10:22.446
but you're wearing
$600 shoes, but...


189
00:10:23.947 --> 00:10:25.782
your ride to the airport

190
00:10:25.866 --> 00:10:27.826
is just pulling away
from the beach,


191
00:10:27.909 --> 00:10:31.496
why, oh, why
is this a legal issue?


192
00:10:34.458 --> 00:10:35.459
I don't know.

193
00:10:37.294 --> 00:10:38.753
It's a matter
of row versus wade.


194
00:10:38.837 --> 00:10:40.005
Oh, my God.

195
00:10:42.048 --> 00:10:43.800
I think that's one of my best.

196
00:10:43.884 --> 00:10:44.885
Wow.

197
00:10:46.928 --> 00:10:47.929
Okay.

198
00:10:51.725 --> 00:10:53.768
- When did you start
smoking again?
-  Mm...


199
00:10:55.729 --> 00:10:57.063
Right after the divorce.

200
00:10:58.815 --> 00:11:00.358
I always hated Larry.

201
00:11:00.442 --> 00:11:01.693
Oh, I know.

202
00:11:01.776 --> 00:11:03.028
You told me
right when we started dating.


203
00:11:03.111 --> 00:11:04.488
Do you remember
how mad I got?


204
00:11:04.696 --> 00:11:05.822
"It's not
your business who I fuck!


205
00:11:06.448 --> 00:11:07.491
Who I fellate."

206
00:11:07.574 --> 00:11:09.951
I definitely
did not say "fellate."


207
00:11:10.035 --> 00:11:12.245
I thought you did.
That's how I heard it anyway.


208
00:11:13.830 --> 00:11:14.956
It's good to see you.

209
00:11:16.917 --> 00:11:18.502
Yeah, it's good
to see you too.


210
00:11:22.172 --> 00:11:23.215
How's work?

211
00:11:24.049 --> 00:11:25.383
It's not very glamorous.

212
00:11:26.843 --> 00:11:29.387
I go through
a metal detector every day.


213
00:11:31.056 --> 00:11:32.766
Well, what you do
is important.


214
00:11:32.849 --> 00:11:33.850
Well...

215
00:11:35.018 --> 00:11:36.853
Meanwhile, all I do is

216
00:11:36.937 --> 00:11:38.605
invent little people
in my head,


217
00:11:38.688 --> 00:11:41.399
then make them have imaginary
conversations with each other.


218
00:11:41.483 --> 00:11:44.277
Books change people's lives.

219
00:11:44.361 --> 00:11:46.696
Did something I've written
ever change your life?


220
00:11:46.780 --> 00:11:48.198
Absolutely.

221
00:11:48.949 --> 00:11:49.950
Absolutely.

222
00:11:51.743 --> 00:11:53.995
My dining room table
was wobbly as hell


223
00:11:54.079 --> 00:11:55.413
before your last book
came out.


224
00:11:55.497 --> 00:11:57.165
- Oh, my God. All right.
- It was, like, perfect.


225
00:11:57.249 --> 00:11:58.500
- Yeah. Oh, God.
- I'm telling you and--


226
00:11:58.583 --> 00:12:00.126
Take me back to Logan, please.

227
00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:01.503
- Logan cannot help you, Monk.

228
00:12:01.586 --> 00:12:03.463
- Oh, my God!

229
00:12:04.381 --> 00:12:05.757
Welcome home, baby!

230
00:12:11.972 --> 00:12:13.223
Hello!

231
00:12:14.099 --> 00:12:15.350
Hello!

232
00:12:19.729 --> 00:12:22.607
- Mr. Monk!
-  Lorraine!


233
00:12:23.275 --> 00:12:25.694
Oh.

234
00:12:25.777 --> 00:12:27.904
You know how
that makes me feel.
It's just Monk.


235
00:12:27.988 --> 00:12:29.364
Oh, don't do that to me,

236
00:12:29.447 --> 00:12:32.075
you know I'm too old
to learn new names.


237
00:12:32.158 --> 00:12:34.160
- How you doing, Miss Lisa?
- I'm good.


238
00:12:34.244 --> 00:12:37.080
- You look good, Mr. Monk.
- Oh, I look fat.


239
00:12:37.163 --> 00:12:39.499
Oh, that's
the California talking.


240
00:12:39.583 --> 00:12:41.042
I took you
to Arkansas right now,


241
00:12:41.126 --> 00:12:42.544
- you'd be a beauty queen.
- Ooh!


242
00:12:42.627 --> 00:12:44.546
-  Is that my Monkie?
- That's frightening.


243
00:12:49.926 --> 00:12:52.971
-  Hi, Mother.
-  Oh.


244
00:12:54.055 --> 00:12:56.516
- You look fat.
- Ah, I know.


245
00:12:56.600 --> 00:12:58.184
You ready
to go to dinner, Mrs. Ellison?


246
00:12:58.268 --> 00:13:00.395
Uh, I just need my purse
and my black cardigan.


247
00:13:00.478 --> 00:13:01.563
All right,
I'll get it.


248
00:13:01.646 --> 00:13:03.231
- Are you all right?
- Oh.


249
00:13:03.315 --> 00:13:05.025
You overeat
when you're depressed.


250
00:13:05.108 --> 00:13:06.776
I'm not depressed,

251
00:13:06.860 --> 00:13:09.571
I've just been
not sleeping well lately


252
00:13:09.654 --> 00:13:11.323
and so,
fell off my exercise routine.


253
